Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00774523 Eh      4.86 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01380127 Eh      8.66 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01913124 Eh     12.01 kcal/mol
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Final entropy term                ...      0.04171502 Eh     26.18 kcal/mol

NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

------------
NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00706808 Eh      4.44 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01381208 Eh      8.67 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01913124 Eh     12.01 kcal/mol
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Final entropy term                ...      0.04104869 Eh     25.76 kcal/mol

NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00705895 Eh      4.43 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01381403 Eh      8.67 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01913124 Eh     12.01 kcal/mol
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Final entropy term                ...      0.04104151 Eh     25.75 kcal/mol

------------
NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

Summary of contributions to the inner energy U:

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00706922 Eh      4.44 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01381234 Eh      8.67 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01913124 Eh     12.01 kcal/mol
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Final entropy term                ...      0.04105009 Eh     25.76 kcal/mol

------------
NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Temperature         ... 298.15 K

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

Summary of contributions to the inner energy U:

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00706748 Eh      4.43 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01381232 Eh      8.67 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01913124 Eh     12.01 kcal/mol
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Final entropy term                ...      0.04104834 Eh     25.76 kcal/mol

------------
NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

                  0          1          2          3          4          5    
      0       0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000
      1       0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000
      2       0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00705896 Eh      4.43 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01381413 Eh      8.67 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01913124 Eh     12.01 kcal/mol
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Final entropy term                ...      0.04104162 Eh     25.75 kcal/mol

NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

Summary of contributions to the inner energy U:

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00706893 Eh      4.44 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01381246 Eh      8.67 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01913124 Eh     12.01 kcal/mol
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Final entropy term                ...      0.04104992 Eh     25.76 kcal/mol

------------
NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Temperature         ... 298.15 K

Total Mass          ... 120.15 AMU

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

Summary of contributions to the inner energy U:

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00706771 Eh      4.44 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01381229 Eh      8.67 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01913124 Eh     12.01 kcal/mol

Final entropy term                ...      0.04104853 Eh     25.76 kcal/mol

------------
NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

THERMOCHEMISTRY AT 298.15K

Temperature         ... 298.15 K

Total Mass          ... 120.15 AMU

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

Summary of contributions to the inner energy U:

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00706627 Eh      4.43 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01381239 Eh      8.67 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01913124 Eh     12.01 kcal/mol
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Final entropy term                ...      0.04104719 Eh     25.76 kcal/mol

NORMAL MODES

M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

      used for the rotational entropy correction. 
 

Note: Rotational entropy computed according to Herzberg 
Infrared and Raman Spectra, Chapter V,1, Van Nostrand Reinhold, 1945 
Point Group:  C1, Symmetry Number:   1  
Rotational constants in cm-1:     0.119767     0.032293     0.028542 

Vibrational entropy computed according to the QRRHO of S. Grimme
Chem.Eur.J. 2012 18 9955


-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00706758 Eh      4.43 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01381227 Eh      8.67 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01913124 Eh     12.01 kcal/mol
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Final entropy term                ...      0.04104838 Eh     25.76 kcal/mol
